ss=3D"shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"displ=
ay:none">Matrix with a multiplicative inverse</div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Lin=
ear algebra">linear algebra</a>, an <b>invertible matrix</b> (<i>non-singul=
ar</i>, <i>non-degenerate</i> or <i>regular</i>) is a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_matrix" title=3D"Square matrix">square matrix</a=
> that has an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicative_inver=
se" title=3D"Multiplicative inverse">inverse</a>. In other words, if a matr=
ix is invertible, it can be multiplied by another matrix to yield the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_matrix" title=3D"Identity matr=
ix">identity matrix</a>. Invertible matrices are the same size as their inv=
erse.
</p><p>The inverse of a matrix represents the inverse operation, meaning if=
 a matrix is applied to a particular vector, followed by applying the matri=
x's inverse, the result is the original vector.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInvertible_matri=
x&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
