<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Newton's_method"><span id=
=3D"Newton.27s_method"></span>Newton's method</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInvertible_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;s=
ection=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Newton's method"><span>edit</span></a><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>A generalization of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newton%27s_=
method" title=3D"Newton's method">Newton's method</a> as used for a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplicative_inverse#Algorithms" title=
=3D"Multiplicative inverse">multiplicative inverse algorithm</a> may be con=
venient if it is convenient to find a suitable starting seed:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e X_{k+1}=3D2X_{k}-X_{k}AX_{k}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mi>X</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <msub>
          <mi>X</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <msub>
          <mi>X</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mi>A</mi>
        <msub>
          <mi>X</mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle X_{k+1}=3D2X_=
{k}-X_{k}AX_{k}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/3f68ddf40974f64ade8d7f5e3be5211ba4c096c3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:22.997ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle X_=
{k+1}=3D2X_{k}-X_{k}AX_{k}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victor_Pan" title=3D"Victor Pan=
">Victor Pan</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Reif" ti=
tle=3D"John Reif">John Reif</a> have done work that includes ways of genera=
ting a starting seed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invertible_matrix#cite_note-3"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Invertible_matrix#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Newton's method is particularly useful when dealing with <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Family_(set_theory)" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Family (set theory)">families</a> of related matrices that behave en=
ough like the sequence manufactured for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Homotopy" title=3D"Homotopy">homotopy</a> above: sometimes a good=
 starting point for refining an approximation for the new inverse can be th=
e already obtained inverse of a previous matrix that nearly matches the cur=
rent matrix. For example, the pair of sequences of inverse matrices used in=
 obtaining <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_square_root#By_D=
enman%E2%80%93Beavers_iteration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Matrix squa=
re root">matrix square roots by Denman=E2=80=93Beavers iteration</a>. That =
may need more than one pass of the iteration at each new matrix, if they ar=
e not close enough together for just one to be enough. Newton's method is a=
lso useful for "touch up" corrections to the Gauss=E2=80=93Jordan algorithm=
 which has been contaminated by small errors from <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Round-off_error" title=3D"Round-off error">imperfect comput=
er arithmetic</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cayley=E2=80=93Hamilton_met=
hod"><span id=3D"Cayley.E2.80.93Hamilton_method"></span>Cayley=E2=80=93Hami=
lton method</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Invertible_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Cayley=E2=80=93Hamilton method"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cayley%E2%80%93Hamilton_the=
orem" title=3D"Cayley=E2=80=93Hamilton theorem">Cayley=E2=80=93Hamilton the=
orem</a> allows the inverse of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> to b=
e expressed in terms of <span class=3D"texhtml">det(<b>A</b>)</span>, trace=
s and powers of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invertible=
_matrix#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \mathbf {A} ^{-1}=3D{\frac {1}{\det(\mathbf {A} )}}\sum _{s=3D0}^{n-1}\ma=
thbf {A} ^{s}\sum _{k_{1},k_{2},\ldots ,k_{n-1}}\prod _{l=3D1}^{n-1}{\frac =
{(-1)^{k_{l}+1}}{l^{k_{l}}k_{l}!}}\operatorname {tr} \left(\mathbf {A} ^{l}=
\right)^{k_{l}},}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msup>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">A</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mfrac>
            <mn>1</mn>
            <mrow>
              <mo movablelimits=3D"true" form=3D"prefix">det</mo>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">A</mi>
              </mrow>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
            </mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <munderover>
          <mo>=E2=88=91<!-- =E2=88=91 --></mo>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>s</mi>
            <mo>=3D</mo>
            <mn>0</mn>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>n</mi>
            <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
            <mn>1</mn>
          </mrow>
        </munderover>
        <msup>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">A</mi>
