ditsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> is a matrix with <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integer</a> or <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D"Rational num=
ber">rational</a> entries, and we seek a solution in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Arbitrary-precision_arithmetic" title=3D"Arbitrary-preci=
sion arithmetic">arbitrary-precision</a> rationals, a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/P-adic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"P-adic"><span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>-adic</a> approxi=
mation method converges to an exact solution in <span class=3D"texhtml">O(<=
i>n</i><sup>4</sup> log<sup>2</sup> <i>n</i>)</span>, assuming standard <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">O(<i>n</i><sup>3</sup>)</span> matrix multiplication i=
s used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Invertible_matrix#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The method rel=
ies on solving <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n<=
/span> linear systems via Dixon's method of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>-adic approximation (each in <span class=
=3D"texhtml">O(<i>n</i><sup>3</sup> log<sup>2</sup> <i>n</i>)</span>) and i=
s available as such in software specialized in arbitrary-precision matrix o=
perations, for example, in IML.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invertible_matrix#cite_note-14"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p>
