://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Continuous_function" title=3D"Continuous function"=
>continuous function</a> because it is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomial</a> in the entries of th=
e matrix. Thus in the language of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Measure_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Measure theory">measure theo=
ry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almost_all" title=3D"Almos=
t all">almost all</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">n</span>-by-<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
n</span> matrices are invertible.
</p><p>Furthermore, the set of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">n</span>-by-<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">n</span> invertible matrices is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Open_set" title=3D"Open set">open</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Dense_set" title=3D"Dense set">dense</a> in the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_space" title=3D"Topological space"=
>topological space</a> of all <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">n</span>-by-<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">n</span> matrices.  Equivalently, the set of singular matrices is <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Closed_set" title=3D"Closed set">cl=
osed</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nowhere_dense" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Nowhere dense">nowhere dense</a> in the space of =
<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>-by-<span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> matrices.
</p><p>In practice, however, non-invertible matrices may be encountered. In=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_analysis" title=3D"Nume=
rical analysis">numerical calculations</a>, matrices that are invertible bu=
t close to a non-invertible matrix may still be problematic and are said to=
 be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Condition_number#Matrices" tit=
le=3D"Condition number">ill-conditioned</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Derivative_of_the_matrix_in=
verse">Derivative of the matrix inverse</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInvertible_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=
=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Derivative of the matrix inverse"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Suppose that the invertible matrix <b>A</b> depends on a parameter <i>t<=
