<p>Non-square matrices, i.e. <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">m</span>-by-<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">n</span> matrices for which <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i> =E2=89=
=A0 <i>n</i></span>, do not have an inverse.  However, in some cases such a=
 matrix may have a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_element=
#Matrices" title=3D"Inverse element">left inverse</a> or <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_element#Matrices" title=3D"Inverse element">=
right inverse</a>. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> is <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span>-by-<span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> and the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rank_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Rank (linear alge=
bra)">rank</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> is equal to <span=
 class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>, (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=
=89=A4 <i>m</i></span>), then <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</b></span> has a=
 left inverse, an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i></span>-by-<span class=3D=
"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"><i>m</i></span> matrix <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>BA</b>=
 =3D <b>I</b><sub><i>n</i></sub></span>.  If <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A</=
b></span> has rank <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i></span> (<span class=3D"=
texhtml"><i>m</i> =E2=89=A4 <i>n</i></span>), then it has a right inverse, =
an <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>-by-<s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">m</span> matrix <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><b>B</b></span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>A=
B</b> =3D <b>I</b><sub><i>m</i></sub></span>.
</p><p>Some of the properties of inverse matrices are shared by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_inverse" title=3D"Generalized inv=
erse">generalized inverses</a> (such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Moore%E2%80%93Penrose_inverse" title=3D"Moore=E2=80=93Penrose inv=
erse">Moore=E2=80=93Penrose inverse</a>), which can be defined for any <i>m=
</i>-by-<i>n</i> matrix.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invertible_matrix#cite_note-18"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_Abstract_algebra">In Abs=
tract algebra</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DInvertible_matrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: In Abstract algebra"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>While the most common case is that of matrices over the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real</a> or <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex numb=
er">complex</a> numbers, all of those definitions can be given for matrices=
 over any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_structure" tit=
le=3D"Algebraic structure">algebraic structure</a> equipped with <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Addition" title=3D"Addition">addition</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication" title=3D"Multipl=
ication">multiplication</a> (i.e. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Ring_(mathematics)" title=3D"Ring (mathematics)">rings</a>). However, in th=
e case of a ring being <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative=
_ring" title=3D"Commutative ring">commutative</a>, the condition for a squa=
re matrix to be invertible is that its determinant is invertible in the rin=
g, which in general is a stricter requirement than it being nonzero. For a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noncommutative_ring" title=3D"Nonc=
ommutative ring">noncommutative ring</a>, the usual determinant is not defi=
ned. The conditions for existence of left-inverse or right-inverse are more=
 complicated, since a notion of rank does not exist over rings.
</p><p>The set of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></span> i=
nvertible matrices together with the operation of <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_multiplication" title=3D"Matrix multiplication">matr=
ix multiplication</a> and entries from ring <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">R</span> form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Group_(mathematics)" title=3D"Group (mathematics)">group</a>, the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_linear_group" title=3D"Gen=
eral linear group">general linear group</a> of degree <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, denoted <span class=3D"texht=
ml">GL<sub><i>n</i></sub>(<i>R</i>)</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInvertible_m=
atrix&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: Applicatio=
ns"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<p>For most practical applications, it is not necessary to invert a matrix =
to solve a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equati=
ons" title=3D"System of linear equations">system of linear equations</a>; h=
owever, for a unique solution, it is necessary for the matrix involved to b=
e invertible.
</p><p>Decomposition techniques like <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/LU_decomposition" title=3D"LU decomposition">LU decomposition</a> are mu=
ch faster than inversion, and various fast algorithms for special classes o=
f linear systems have also been developed.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Regression/least_squares"><=
span id=3D"Regression.2Fleast_squares"></span>Regression/least squares</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInvertible_matri=
x&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit section: Regression/lea=
st squares"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Although an explicit inverse is not necessary to estimate the vector of =
unknowns, it is the easiest way to estimate their accuracy and is found in =
the diagonal of a matrix inverse (the posterior covariance matrix of the ve=
ctor of unknowns). However, faster algorithms to compute only the diagonal =
entries of a matrix inverse are known in many cases.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invertible_ma=
trix#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Matrix_inverses_in_real-tim=
e_simulations">Matrix inverses in real-time simulations</h3><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInvertible_matrix&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: Matrix inverses in real-time =
simulations"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>Matrix inversion plays a significant role in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Computer_graphics" title=3D"Computer graphics">computer graph=
ics</a>, particularly in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/3D_graphi=
cs" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"3D graphics">3D graphics</a> rendering a=
nd <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D3D_simulations&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"3D simulations (pa=
ge does not exist)">3D simulations</a>. Examples include screen-to-world <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_casting" title=3D"Ray casting">r=
ay casting</a>, world-to-subspace-to-world object transformations, and phys=
ical simulations.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Matrix_inverses_in_MIMO_wir=
eless_communication">Matrix inverses in MIMO wireless communication</h3><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DInvertible_matrix&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section: Matrix inverses i=
n MIMO wireless communication"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Matrix inversion also plays a significant role in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MIMO" title=3D"MIMO">MIMO</a> (Multiple-Input, Multi=
ple-Output) technology in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wireless=
_communications" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wireless communications">wi=
reless communications</a>. The MIMO system consists of <i>N</i> transmit an=
d <i>M</i> receive antennas. Unique signals, occupying the same <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequency_band" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Frequency band">frequency band</a>, are sent via <i>N</i> transmit ante=
nnas and are received via <i>M</i> receive antennas. The signal arriving at=
 each receive antenna will be a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li=
near_combination" title=3D"Linear combination">linear combination</a> of th=
e <i>N</i> transmitted signals forming an <i>N</i>&nbsp;=C3=97&nbsp;<i>M</i=
> transmission matrix <b>H</b>. It is crucial for the matrix <b>H</b> to be=
 invertible so that the receiver can figure out the transmitted information=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Invertible_matrix#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
